1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:09,000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

2
00:00:09,000 --> 00:00:11,000
Great.

3
00:00:11,000 --> 00:00:16,000
Okay, so I'm just going to introduce all of us first and then we'll start the interview.

4
00:00:16,000 --> 00:00:21,000
So today is June 22nd, 2013. I'm in Louisville, Kentucky.

5
00:00:21,000 --> 00:00:25,000
This is David Cline speaking from the History Department at Virginia Tech,

6
00:00:25,000 --> 00:00:30,000
also working with the Southern Oral History Program at UNC Chapel Hill.

7
00:00:30,000 --> 00:00:37,000
Recording this interview for the Civil Rights History Project of the National Museum of African American History and Culture,

8
00:00:37,000 --> 00:00:41,000
the Smithsonian and the Library of Congress.

9
00:00:41,000 --> 00:00:45,000
Behind the camera today is John Bishop from UCLA and Media Generation,

10
00:00:45,000 --> 00:00:49,000
and very pleased to be speaking with Walter Tillow today in Louisville.

11
00:00:49,000 --> 00:00:57,000
If you could introduce yourself, tell us where you were born in your age and then we'll start a conversation.

12
00:00:57,000 --> 00:01:04,000
I'm 73 years old. I was born in New York City and raised in the Bronx in New York City.

13
00:01:04,000 --> 00:01:10,000
Okay, and as I said off camera, I like to start with people's childhoods.

14
00:01:10,000 --> 00:01:18,000
And as you can tell us a little bit about your family and if you see any influences from your family or your upbringing,

15
00:01:18,000 --> 00:01:23,000
that may have influenced your work later on.

16
00:01:23,000 --> 00:01:28,000
Well, as I said, I was born in the Bronx, New York City.

17
00:01:28,000 --> 00:01:34,000
My mother worked for the State of New York in the Unemployment Insurance Division.

18
00:01:34,000 --> 00:01:41,000
And my dad was a, had a small business in washing machines, laundromats,

19
00:01:41,000 --> 00:01:47,000
type of, just becoming technology coin operated laundry.

20
00:01:47,000 --> 00:01:54,000
I grew up in a basically middle class lifestyle.

21
00:01:54,000 --> 00:02:00,000
My parents had been radicals members of the Young Communists League in the 1920s,

22
00:02:00,000 --> 00:02:07,000
although the depression and family kind of calmed them down.

23
00:02:07,000 --> 00:02:10,000
You know, they kind of went on to other things.

24
00:02:10,000 --> 00:02:19,000
But that was a background in my growing up, the Cold War.

25
00:02:19,000 --> 00:02:26,000
The execution of Rosenbergs was something that I was 13 at the time.

26
00:02:26,000 --> 00:02:35,000
I remember a discussion in the kitchen between my mom and dad as to whether my mother should go to the funeral.

27
00:02:35,000 --> 00:02:40,000
They were executed on a Friday. The funeral was according to Jewish law.

28
00:02:40,000 --> 00:02:45,000
It had to be buried 24 hours, so the funeral was sanity.

29
00:02:45,000 --> 00:02:48,000
And they eventually decided that my mother shouldn't go.

30
00:02:48,000 --> 00:02:53,000
And so my father insisted on taking me with him.

31
00:02:53,000 --> 00:03:02,000
And so that was a memorable impact on my, and also I had a half of the family that was kind of radical.

32
00:03:02,000 --> 00:03:09,000
The other half was conservative. And so, you know, family arguments through the Cold War.

33
00:03:09,000 --> 00:03:19,000
I kind of was aware of progressive left politics, you know, and Soviet Union, socialism, and so forth.

34
00:03:19,000 --> 00:03:24,000
But your parents radicalism was sort of, it's a little bit removed at that point.

35
00:03:24,000 --> 00:03:30,000
Yeah, they weren't the members. They weren't subscribers.

36
00:03:30,000 --> 00:03:36,000
I had an aunt who was a subscriber. I had another aunt who was a member of Communist Party.

37
00:03:36,000 --> 00:03:43,000
But I didn't know that. And, you know, I knew them as aunts and, you know, as I say, progressive arguments.

38
00:03:43,000 --> 00:03:48,000
For me and my family, it was not, you know, nothing was in family life.

39
00:03:48,000 --> 00:03:53,000
Meetings or something like that. No, it was no.

40
00:03:53,000 --> 00:03:58,000
It was sort of a basic middle class existence, 1950s.

41
00:03:58,000 --> 00:04:08,000
What about race issues in New York at that time when you were growing up? Any impact?

42
00:04:08,000 --> 00:04:19,000
My sister had a friend in school. My folks became friends with her family, her parents, you know, they became socially acquainted.

43
00:04:19,000 --> 00:04:27,000
At that time in New York, there was, I grew up right outside of Parkchester.

44
00:04:27,000 --> 00:04:36,000
Parkchester was the largest development, private development apartments funded by Metropolitan Life.

45
00:04:36,000 --> 00:04:43,000
And it was segregated, although it wasn't officially segregated, they just wouldn't rent the African Americans.

46
00:04:43,000 --> 00:04:53,000
And on the rent control, you had to keep an apartment vacant for one year in order to decontrol it.

47
00:04:53,000 --> 00:05:04,000
So, Metropolitan Life would, somebody would move out of Parkchester, they would keep the apartment vacant for a year, you know, and then it would become decontrolled.

48
00:05:04,000 --> 00:05:12,000
So, there was a housing movement. It wasn't only in Louisville at the time. That's the (Anne and Carl) Bradens origin, you know, same movement.

49
00:05:12,000 --> 00:05:19,000
So, it would change themselves to the door, you know, on these vacant apartments, there was a movement to try and get met life, you know.

50
00:05:19,000 --> 00:05:30,000
So, I was aware of that kind of a movement, but other than that, we didn't participate, you know, it was just my sister's friends, parents lived in Parkchester.

51
00:05:30,000 --> 00:05:41,000
So, we kind of knew, they didn't participate either, but you kind of got reports, you know, there was an incident, you know, people would change themselves to the door in this building, you know, and kind of talk.

52
00:05:41,000 --> 00:06:02,000
You know, that way. But other than that, as I say to Rosenbergs, you know, the Cold War more, I came upon my father, you know, in the garage one day, you know, the thrown out, literally it collected, you know, newspapers, and, you know, he kind of showed me, he was getting rid of it.

53
00:06:02,000 --> 00:06:20,000
And another incident, I had a, my aunt lived in Westchester County, my uncle was an artist and a cartoonist. So, it was a rural, at that time it was rural, rural, upstate New York, you know, and all those and too far from New York City.

54
00:06:20,000 --> 00:06:46,000
And some friends at AIS had given them some books. Actually, they gave them a collection of the works of Lenin because they had to get them out of there. They felt they couldn't keep them in their, in their apartment in New York and people came, you know, this, it was that kind of an atmosphere that Cold War atmosphere was, you know, kind of impinged upon your, your consciousness, you know, whatever.

55
00:06:46,000 --> 00:06:55,000
But, but those are just incidents, you know, looking back, you know, kind of at the time when I was in college, she gave me the 13 volumes, you know, she was.

56
00:06:55,000 --> 00:07:13,000
So, so I mean, I actually got a collected works of Lenin, you know, when I was in college because she had been holding of somebody, they finally said the hell would have, you know, thrown away and rather than thrown away she gave me.

57
00:07:13,000 --> 00:07:20,000
So, yeah.

58
00:07:20,000 --> 00:07:31,000
Okay. Fantastic. So, what, I guess you could tell us a little bit about college and sort of what brought you into the movement.

59
00:07:31,000 --> 00:07:36,000
I don't know if there's one moment or if it was a gradual process.

60
00:07:36,000 --> 00:07:42,000
Well, I went to a Harpur College, which was a state university in New York.

61
00:07:42,000 --> 00:07:50,000
At that time it was, it was in a bunch of quants and huts and converted mansions and endocut in New York.

62
00:07:50,000 --> 00:07:56,000
And now it's a, it's a big graduate center campus and best of, you know, nearby.

63
00:07:56,000 --> 00:08:14,000
When I started it was, it was a school that relied mainly on vets coming back on the G.I. Bill, you know, and 1960 I was a junior and the sitting movement broke out.

64
00:08:14,000 --> 00:08:23,000
And we decided, we had a lot of kids from New York City at the school because it was cheap.

65
00:08:23,000 --> 00:08:30,000
I think tuition at that time was $300 a year and they went on a dorm so you could live off, you know, when I went there, they went on a dorm.

66
00:08:30,000 --> 00:08:35,000
When I finished there, what dorms? But when I went there, they went on a dorm so you had to live off campus.

67
00:08:35,000 --> 00:08:44,000
So, you know, it drew a lot of, you know, people that didn't want to go to city college but wanted to go to, couldn't afford a private school.

68
00:08:44,000 --> 00:08:49,000
So we got to evolve with the picketing Walmart.

69
00:08:49,000 --> 00:08:59,000
We wanted a first, second school to picket, have a sympathy demonstration at the local, not Walmart.

70
00:09:00,000 --> 00:09:03,000
Woolworth, Woolworth Company.

71
00:09:03,000 --> 00:09:19,000
You know, the administration fought as Bentley, you know, and we had this argument with student government and actually we found a clipping that Harvard did it and that was kind of convinced student government that we could do it.

72
00:09:19,000 --> 00:09:33,000
So, you know, so we picket it into the Woolworth and Johnson City, you know, but that was kind of, that was the first, you know, kind of way for that.

73
00:09:33,000 --> 00:09:36,000
Thank you.

74
00:09:36,000 --> 00:09:45,000
That was like, we responded to the times, you know, sitting, moving, broke out, you know, it made perfect sense, you know, segregation.

75
00:09:45,000 --> 00:09:51,000
You know, we had Woolworth, you know, all over the place at that time, they all had countless, lunch, countless and so forth.

76
00:09:51,000 --> 00:10:07,000
So, that was when I was a junior and we went on to some more radical activities that, when I between, in my senior year, we were moved on to the new campus, which we had to live on the campus, you know, and they needed the money.

77
00:10:07,000 --> 00:10:10,000
So, they made everybody on the campus.

78
00:10:10,000 --> 00:10:23,000
So, we had, you know, we got involved there at that time in New York State, at that time nationally, but in New York State they had a one day shelter drill.

79
00:10:23,000 --> 00:10:34,000
It was in the Cold War, you know, afraid the Soviets would win a bomb, nuclear bombs, you had to find the shelter, you know, and so they rang of siren and noon all over the state.

80
00:10:34,000 --> 00:10:37,000
People had to take cover, you know, it was in campus.

81
00:10:37,000 --> 00:10:50,000
So, there were a couple of passivists on, you know, in the school and we heard that they were going to go have a picnic rather than, you know, they're going to go in the woods, you know, it was sort of a rural campus.

82
00:10:50,000 --> 00:11:02,000
So, we said, well, let's just stand outside in the quage, you know, and so we had 50, 60, 70 kids, you know, defied the take cover drill, you know, and stood out there.

83
00:11:02,000 --> 00:11:14,000
The president called hell, you know, he was, you know, we had a dean that had some principal and he stood up for us, but, you know, one thing went to another.

84
00:11:14,000 --> 00:11:21,000
And from there, somebody had an idea, not me.

85
00:11:21,000 --> 00:11:33,000
There was a young Democrats, a young Republicans, we were going to organize a young socialists and we organized it, meaning you got money from a student government.

86
00:11:33,000 --> 00:11:35,000
So, it was an official organization?

87
00:11:35,000 --> 00:11:43,000
You recognize student organization and we invited a comment, well, we invited a social worker person to speak.

88
00:11:43,000 --> 00:11:55,000
Nobody knew, you know, the name would pop up, yeah, you know. And because of us, the air raid drill protest, the president forbid her to speak even harder from the campus.

89
00:11:55,000 --> 00:12:11,000
And the faculty was, because the state paid better in the lower positions, you know, assistant and lecturer, you know, we had a lot of future names, you know,

90
00:12:11,000 --> 00:12:31,000
that took a job out of graduates to pay off loans because the money was better. So, it was in a conscious, you know, where smart faculty, and they kind of took away his power to bar anybody from speaking on campus as a result of that barring that that social worker party candidate.

91
00:12:31,000 --> 00:12:50,000
The next name that came up was a guy named Herbert Aptheker. He was a prominent communist historian, Ph.D. from Columbia. And we had a big battle over him, you know, the American Legion threatened to pick it, you know, the president wanted to bar him, but he couldn't do it.

92
00:12:50,000 --> 00:13:08,000
You know, the question came up, what are you going to charge money and not charge money and to admit it. The result was that place was packed, seven, eight hundred people in the newly opened auditorium, you know, and another impact on me was a particularly effective public speaker.

93
00:13:08,000 --> 00:13:24,000
So, you know, that was sort of my academic career, you know, when I went out to the University of Washington as a graduate student the next year, there was another fight. I wasn't involved in other than to attend his lecture, but he was barred from speaking at the University of Washington.

94
00:13:24,000 --> 00:13:37,000
Same thing, he spoke off campus, you know, and I attended the meeting. And so I had some contact that way, you know, with progressive ideas, radical ideas, in some case, at the University of Washington, actually.

95
00:13:37,000 --> 00:13:52,000
There was some young communists that organized that meeting and I got to know them. But, and Cornell. So that was, I went to University of Washington as a graduate student, 61, 62.

96
00:13:52,000 --> 00:13:53,000
What were you studying?

97
00:13:53,000 --> 00:14:06,000
Economic history. And then I went back to Cornell, 62, 63 as a graduate student. At Cornell, we had sort of a kind of a breakfast.

98
00:14:06,000 --> 00:14:19,000
You know, a group of us graduate students, undergraduates, we'd meet every morning for breakfast in the student activity center. I forget what it was called.

99
00:14:19,000 --> 00:14:35,000
There was a big major strike of the newspapers in New York City. It was a strike over technology. The printers were striking to bar, you know, cold type technology.

100
00:14:35,000 --> 00:14:48,000
It was, it was a line of type days and, you know, they wanted to go to cold type, what eventually. And it was a long strike. And, you know, in a place like Cornell, the New York Times not being, you know, everybody was starving.

101
00:14:48,000 --> 00:15:04,000
So somebody had a bright idea that we could, we could read various, and in deference to the New York Times, since it was, you know, a major issue for the whole industry.

102
00:15:04,000 --> 00:15:08,000
Other newspapers of Washington Post, they wouldn't send in copies.

103
00:15:08,000 --> 00:15:27,000
The areas were at a New York Times. So, as I say, people were starving, you know. So somebody had a bright idea if we subscribed to a variety of, or read them in the library and came in once a week with clippings of, you know, then we would reproduce them and put them up around campus.

104
00:15:27,000 --> 00:15:43,000
So, somehow I got to read the Baltimore-African-American. That was my choice. And we would bring any articles. Somebody would paste them up and duplicate it. And then we would post it up around the campus.

105
00:15:43,000 --> 00:15:57,000
And the annual SNCC convention, the Easter meeting came up in Afro-American. It was in April of 1963. So, a couple of us decided to go.

106
00:15:57,000 --> 00:16:10,000
And I went, you know, a car loan of us went, and that's where I met Anne Braden. And that's how I got involved. You know, that's the story of how I got involved.

107
00:16:10,000 --> 00:16:24,000
But you had read about it and just gotten the car and went. Well, we know it was an announcement. You know, they covered the story about SNCC's annual Easter conference.

108
00:16:24,000 --> 00:16:35,000
At that time, they had founded 1960. So, this is like the third, you know, third Easter conference of the Student of Bioanca Women Committee. So...

109
00:16:35,000 --> 00:16:36,000
And where was it, Helen?

110
00:16:36,000 --> 00:16:40,000
And it was held in Gammon Theological Seminary in Atlanta.

111
00:16:40,000 --> 00:16:45,000
And the Old Gammond, you know, the Old Theological Seminary.

112
00:16:45,000 --> 00:16:46,000
So...

113
00:16:46,000 --> 00:16:48,000
It became inter-denominational.

114
00:16:48,000 --> 00:16:49,000
Right, right.

115
00:16:50,000 --> 00:16:57,000
So, we were looking. No, we had an idea about the summer... You know, going south for the summer. A couple of us.

116
00:16:57,000 --> 00:17:04,000
And the only person that would talk with us seriously and had an idea was Anne.

117
00:17:04,000 --> 00:17:12,000
She suggested that Fayette County, Tennessee, you know, the movement there needed some people.

118
00:17:12,000 --> 00:17:24,000
So, three of us, you know, Bunny Haney + Charlie Haney, he was a mathematics, his wife, bunny, and their infant baby, you know, a month old.

119
00:17:24,000 --> 00:17:32,000
A couple of months old, and they went down to myself, went to Fayette County, Tennessee for that summer of 1963.

120
00:17:32,000 --> 00:17:36,000
We must have got there, May, June.

121
00:17:36,000 --> 00:17:38,000
Stayed through to March on Washington.

122
00:17:38,000 --> 00:17:46,000
In other words, and Fayette County was a...

123
00:17:46,000 --> 00:17:58,000
It was a place where in the 1930s, the federal government had tried an experiment in terms of increasing black land ownership.

124
00:17:58,000 --> 00:18:03,000
There was a WPA or, I don't know, was WPA.

125
00:18:03,000 --> 00:18:08,000
But it was some project to increase black ownership of land.

126
00:18:08,000 --> 00:18:11,000
Eleanor Roosevelt, you know, was involved.

127
00:18:11,000 --> 00:18:20,000
So, there was a county that was probably nine... Two counties there, just east of Memphis Shelby County.

128
00:18:20,000 --> 00:18:23,000
They sit right on the Mississippi board.

129
00:18:23,000 --> 00:18:28,000
They were like an extension of the Delta, Fayette and Haywood County.

130
00:18:28,000 --> 00:18:38,000
But they had... While they were 90% African-American, they had a high percentage of black land owned their own land, you know, in the county.

131
00:18:38,000 --> 00:18:42,000
Although they had a sharecropping system for whites.

132
00:18:42,000 --> 00:18:52,000
And there was a case, a criminal case where a preacher was charged with murder and he fled the county.

133
00:18:52,000 --> 00:18:56,000
And he had come back. This is before my...

134
00:18:56,000 --> 00:19:06,000
And the lawyers that defended him, they asked every perspective juror, do they have any problem with African-Americans voting?

135
00:19:06,000 --> 00:19:12,000
Because he couldn't serve on a jury unless you're on a voting rolls in those days.

136
00:19:12,000 --> 00:19:15,000
So, of course, everybody answered, no, they had no problem.

137
00:19:15,000 --> 00:19:25,000
So, there were a number of Vets, Korean War Vets, were two Vets that, you know, had attended the trial because of the prominence of the minister.

138
00:19:25,000 --> 00:19:30,000
And they heard everybody say, well, we don't object to African-Americans voting.

139
00:19:30,000 --> 00:19:34,000
So, they went out to try and erole African-Americans.

140
00:19:34,000 --> 00:19:42,000
And that's the origin of the movement that whites retaliated by expelling sharecroppers from the land.

141
00:19:42,000 --> 00:19:45,000
Because they were African-Americans that owned their own farms.

142
00:19:45,000 --> 00:19:51,000
They set up tents on Black-owned land to house sharecroppers that had been expelled.

143
00:19:51,000 --> 00:20:00,000
And there was a movement guy, a minister, and since then I had Marcheka McCracken, and there was some sort of a community church.

144
00:20:00,000 --> 00:20:02,000
I think it was called a community church.

145
00:20:02,000 --> 00:20:04,000
Got involved, and the (Anne and Carl) Bradens got involved.

146
00:20:04,000 --> 00:20:08,000
And there was a big movement in Chicago to support tent city.

147
00:20:08,000 --> 00:20:11,000
It became tent city.

148
00:20:11,000 --> 00:20:19,000
And it so happens that they were sending food and clothes because the winner was chilly.

149
00:20:19,000 --> 00:20:24,000
Who was organizing on the ground, the core local organizing?

150
00:20:24,000 --> 00:20:31,000
I don't know who was in that time, it was before my day, there were night-ride people who would ride by and shoot into the tents.

151
00:20:31,000 --> 00:20:37,000
It got some national publicity at the time in the 50s.

152
00:20:37,000 --> 00:20:46,000
But the movement in Chicago, you know, there were unions, a guy named Jesse Prosten, and from the pack-and-house workers, his wife, and some others.

153
00:20:46,000 --> 00:20:51,000
They hired somebody to kind of coordinate between Chicago and the whole movement.

154
00:20:51,000 --> 00:20:54,000
And that guy, if they hired, was James (Jim) Forman.

155
00:20:54,000 --> 00:20:58,000
And became executive director of SNCC.

156
00:20:58,000 --> 00:21:01,000
So when I got to Fayette County,

157
00:21:01,000 --> 00:21:04,000
I had no...

158
00:21:04,000 --> 00:21:10,000
Foreman was in Atlanta as the executive director of SNCC.

159
00:21:10,000 --> 00:21:12,000
But had been in...

160
00:21:12,000 --> 00:21:17,000
But he had this role, you know, as coordinated down and back, you know, with supplies.

161
00:21:17,000 --> 00:21:19,000
And as I say, had national attention.

162
00:21:19,000 --> 00:21:23,000
There were other, you know, there were efforts to self-help projects.

163
00:21:23,000 --> 00:21:28,000
You know, there was an effort to set up a making leather book bags.

164
00:21:28,000 --> 00:21:38,000
Or, you know, in Haywood County, I think, you know, there was some project to kind of build homes for these people on land that was purchased.

165
00:21:38,000 --> 00:21:43,000
Because we stayed in an uncompleted home.

166
00:21:43,000 --> 00:21:47,000
I mean, I did. I think the Haneys, with the baby, they stayed with some family.

167
00:21:47,000 --> 00:21:54,000
But I stayed in a vacant house interior just no walls, you know, framed, but no walls, no plumbing.

168
00:21:54,000 --> 00:21:56,000
You know, I just were able to sleep there.

169
00:21:56,000 --> 00:22:01,000
But we took a trip to Atlanta in the middle of the summer.

170
00:22:01,000 --> 00:22:03,000
That's where I met Forman,

171
00:22:03,000 --> 00:22:07,000
And he had this affection for Fayette County because of his involvement there.

172
00:22:07,000 --> 00:22:09,000
So he kind of took an interest.

173
00:22:09,000 --> 00:22:17,000
And while I was there, you know, there were a couple of teenagers, two or three teenagers that were in hot water.

174
00:22:17,000 --> 00:22:21,000
The police were looking for them in South Georgia, in Albany.

175
00:22:21,000 --> 00:22:27,000
And so, Charles Sherrod wanted to get them out of, so they sent them back.

176
00:22:27,000 --> 00:22:30,000
They asked if I could keep them in Fayette County.

177
00:22:30,000 --> 00:22:35,000
So they came back with me and they spent the summer.

178
00:22:35,000 --> 00:22:38,000
And that was a summer of March in Washington.

179
00:22:38,000 --> 00:22:45,000
So there was, you know, several buses from Fayette and Haywood County went to the March.

180
00:22:45,000 --> 00:22:46,000
Went to the March.

